@NODE "Introduction_Node" "Introduction"
@TOC "MAIN"
@{b}iNTRODUCTIOn@{ub}
@{b}~~~~~~~~~~~~@{ub}

           ... here is the pASSWORD sECURITY V1.4 /X Door by rEAL ...


  Features:

          - the syspw is fully configurable (but limited to 30 chars)
          - all wrong syspw's the user entered will be saved
            to a logfile
          - fully configurable pwsansi.txt and pwsend.txt file
          - no difference between upper/lowercase letters
          - all code written in pure C language
          - 68000, 68020+ versions
          - Because of @{b}NO BACKDOOR@{ub} NO RISK
            Disassemble the code if ya don't believe me !!!

  NEW Features in V1.2:

          - the logfile for wrong syspw's will be created with regard to
            the node at which the user logsin
            for example: DOORS:rEAL/Pws/Data/Node0 <-- Logfile for Node 0
                         DOORS:rEAL/Pws/Data/Node1 <-- Logfile for Node 1
          - all wrong syspw's will be saved with date and time of input
          - Because of @{b}NO BACKDOOR@{ub} NO RISK
            Disassemble the code if ya don't believe me !!!

  NEW Features in V1.3:

          - V1.3 of my door and all other rEAL-dOORS in future will need
            the rEALdOOR.library in Libs: to run

          - Tooltype-Features added
            You can choose by the CONOUTPUT-tooltype if the syspw shall
            be displayed to console or not
            You can choose by the TEXT-tooltype if a textstring shall be
            displayed instead of a star (*).
          - Because of @{b}NO BACKDOOR@{ub} NO RISK
            Disassemble the code if ya don't believe me !!!

  NEW Features in V1.4:

          - hardcoded filenames for logfile and other removed
          - now FULL Tooltype support !!!
          - you can use your own prompt
          - number of tries for syspw configurable up to 9999 times
          - Added the following Tooltypes:

            SYSPW, SYSPWCOUNT, LOGPATH, PROMPT, ADVERT, PWFAIL

          - Because of @{b}NO BACKDOOR@{ub} NO RISK
            Disassemble the code if ya don't believe me !!!



@ENDNODE

@NODE "Requirements_Node" "Requirements"
@TOC "MAIN"
@{b}rEQUIREMENTs@{ub}
@{b}~~~~~~~~~~~~@{ub}

                            Everyone can run it!!!

          - you only need an AMIGA
          - KS2.04 or higher
          - the great AmiExpress V4.x
          - the AEDoor.library V2.4+ in Libs:
          - and rEALdOOR.library in Libs: (included in this archive)

          @{b}pASSWORd sECURITy V1.4@{ub} should also work with @{b}S!X@{ub} and @{b}FAME@{ub}
          but it wasn't tried yet.


@ENDNODE

@NODE "Installation_Node" "Installation"
@TOC "MAIN"
@{b}iNSTALLATIOn@{ub}
@{b}~~~~~~~~~~~~@{ub}

                      The installation is very simple...

   - copy the rEALdOOR.library to Libs:
   - copy the directory rEAL with all the files to DOORS:
   - copy the directory COMMANDS with all the files to BBS:
   - include the following lines in the BBSTitle.txt in BBS:Screens/node<x>
     or Node<x> Directory:

       ~
       ~f      <-- don't forget a "space" behind the f !!! IMPORTANT !!!
       ~CC_PWS|

     Maybe you have to create the "BBSTitle.txt" file at first !!

   - remove the SYSTEM_PASSWORD Tooltype from your Node<x>.info ICON
   - remove the SYS_PWD_PROMPT Tooltype from your Node<x>.info ICON
   - makesure that your internal computer-clock shows the right time
     and date

   ready...


   nOTE: nEVER START ANSI oR aN oTHER dOOR bEFORE tHE sYSPW-dOOR!
         cOZ u lOST sECURITY .............
   


@ENDNODE

@NODE "Working_Node" "Working"
@TOC "MAIN"
@{b}wORKINg@{ub}
@{b}~~~~~~~@{ub}

   This Door asks every User who logsin for the SYSPW you have chosen.
   He has 3 chances to typein the right Syspw.
   If he failed, he will get a CARRIER LOST.
   All wrong SYPWs will be logged to a logfile of your choice.



@ENDNODE

@NODE "Configuration_Node" "Configuration"
@TOC "MAIN"
@{b}cONFIGURATIOn@{ub}
@{b}~~~~~~~~~~~~~@{ub}

  You can configurate the door. My door uses the standard /X-Tooltypes !

  PWS.info ICON:

  Tooltypes:
     ACCESS
     TYPE
     LOCATION
     MULTINODE
     CONOUTPUT  ( NEW in V1.3 !!!)
     TEXT       ( NEW in V1.3 !!!)
     SYSPW      ( NEW in V1.4 !!!)
     SYSPWCOUNT ( NEW in V1.4 !!!)
     LOGPATH    ( NEW in V1.4 !!!)
     PROMPT     ( NEW in V1.4 !!!)
     ADVERT     ( NEW in V1.4 !!!)
     PWFAIL     ( NEW in V1.4 !!!)

  ACCESS:
     Pattern : ACCESS= <num>
     Function: Tells /X the access level required to run this module.
               This option is ignored for internal Module options.
     Example : ACCESS=10
               Check for a level about 10 or higher.

  TYPE:
     Pattern : TYPE= < XIM | AIM | TIM | IIM | SIM | MCI >
     Function: This is the type of door you use.
     Example : TYPE=XIM
               For my door the TYPE should be XIM !!!

  LOCATION:
     Pattern : LOCATION= <string>
     Function: Specifies the location of the module
     Example1: LOCATION=DOORS:rEAL/PWS/PWS00.exe
               If you are using the version for 68000 CPUs !

     Example2: LOCATION=DOORS:rEAL/PWS/PWS020.exe
               If you are using the version for 68020 CPUs !

     Example3: LOCATION=DOORS:rEAL/PWS/PWS030.exe
               If you are using the version for 68030 CPUs !

     Example4: LOCATION=DOORS:rEAL/PWS/PWS0x0.exe
               If you are using the version for 68040/60 CPUs !

  MULTINODE:
     Pattern : MULTINODE= <YES|NO>
     Function: Tells /X if the module may be simultaneously accessed
               from other nodes.

  CONOUTPUT:
     Pattern : CONOUTPUT= <YES|NO>
     Function: Tells "Password Security" if the syspw which the user
               enters shall be displayed to console in readable
               way or not.
               The syspw will be displayed to CONSOLE ONLY, that means
               only the SYSOP or the guy at the CONSOLE-SIDE can see
               it !!!
     Example1: CONOUTPUT=YES

     Example2: CONOUTPUT=NO

  TEXT:
     Pattern : TEXT= <Textstring>
     Function: If you use this option the textstring behind "TEXT="
               will be displayed to the user and sysop instead of a star.
               The textstring will NOT be displayed to the sysop if the
               CONOUTPUT-tooltype is activated (CONOUTPUT=YES) !!!
     Example1: TEXT=rEAL!
               If a user types in the syspw, the textstring "rEAL!" will
               be displayed to him (and if CONOUTPUT=NO to the sysop too)
               instead of a star.
               The lenght of the textstring should be as long as the lenght
               of the syspw is (it looks nicer) but not more than 30 chars
               are allowed.
     Example2: TEXT=fUCK!
               and the syspw is LUNIZ.

               fUCK! <--| The textstring and the syspw
               LUNIZ <--| have the same lenght.

     Example3: TEXT=Hello
               and the syspw is BOYSCOUT

               Hello    <--| The textstring and the syspw
               BOYSCOUT <--| have NOT the same lenght (it doesn't looks nice).

               IMPORTANT !!!! IMPORTANT !!!! IMPORTANT !!!! IMPORTANT !!!!
               The textstring will also be displayed if you have chosen
               a SPACE as textstring. That's why you should make sure,
               that behind the "=" there is no SPACE if you have
               deactivated the tooltype in the following way:
               TEXT=           <--- ALL text (also SPACES) behind
                                    the "=" must be deleted !!!

               It's better if you deactivate the tooltype in that way:
               (TEXT=)

               because then you can be sure, that it is REALLY
               deactivated.

  SYSPW:
     Pattern : SYSPW= <Systempassword>
     Function: The Systempassword you want to use for access to your
               board. (Lenght of syspw limited to 30 chars)

  SYSPWCOUNT:
     Pattern : SYSPWCOUNT= <Number>
     Function: The number of chances to enter the right syspw.
               (the maximum number is 9999... that's enough i think)

  LOGPATH:
     Pattern : LOGPATH= <Path and filename of logfile>
     Function: The path and filename to write the logfile with wrong
               syspw's to.
               (Lenght of string not more than 50 chars)
     Example : LOGPATH=DOORS:rEAL/Pws/syspwfailed.txt
               All wrong syspw's will be logged to "syspwfailed.txt"
               in "DOORS:rEAL/Pws/" .
               If ya run the door on "Node 0" the full name of the
               logfile would be "syspwfailed.txt0".
               The node-number will be merged to the filename.
               Remember that the complete path with all it's
               directories must exists or the logfile won't be saved.

  PROMPT:
     Pattern : PROMPT= <String for Prompt>
     Function: The Promptstring that shall be displayed if the user
               is asked for the syspw.
               (Lenght of string not more than 50 chars)

  ADVERT:
     Pattern : ADVERT= <Path and filename of advert>
     Function: The path and filename of an advert (text/ansi) that
               will be displayed to the user before syspw-input.
               (Lenght of string not more than 50 chars)

  PWFAIL:
     Pattern : PWFAIL= <Path and filename of logoffansi>
     Function: The path and filename of an text/ansi that will be
               displayed to the user if he entered a wrong syspw
               3 times.
               (Lenght of string not more than 50 chars)



@ENDNODE

